Around 13 trading sessions left until 12/30 - and in order for MSFT (2nd place) to overtake AAPL, MSFT has to go up on average 0.81% while AAPL drops 0.67% for every trading session until the question closes. Similarly, if Saudi Aramco overtakes AAPL (neglecting what MSFT does), it has to go up on average 1.08% while AAPL drops 0.84% for every trading session until year-end.
currently Dec 6 - and Apple is most valuable in the world 2.281T (next up is Saudi Aramco with 1.881T)
The gap has narrowed by nearly 5% today. I'll hedge a little more.

Both Apple and Aramco have a China problem -- Apple for the unrest shutting down iPhone 14 Pro production and Aramco because the lockdowns are decreasing oil consumption. So far the effects seem to offset each other, with both stocks falling over 2.5% today. I'll stay at 87% for AAPL for now, and watch as events unfold.

I suspect that most of the iPhones Apple will sell before 2023 have already been made. But equity prices are determined by events that happen on the margin. Incremental news, both good and bad, quickly get priced into a stock.
Aramco down by 20% now with six weeks left

As of today:

ARAMCO will have to rise nearly 20% to catch AAPL, which seems unlikely to me. Not impossible, but unlikely. An interesting question is whether Microsoft's value will exceed ARAMCO. I'd give that a 35-50% chance.

Apple actually had somewhat of a weak quarter, with revenues shrinking year over year when adjusted for inflation. By contrast Microsoft had strong growth, as did Alphabet. And yet, the stock market in the short run is all about how a company does compared with expectations, so for that reason Apple is up.

ARAMCO now has an 11% gap to make up to surpass AAPL. Some forecasters have moved more towards Apple, but overall the crowd still gives ARAMCO a one in three chance of coming out on top by the end of the year. The crowd could be right in its caution. However, I'll stay with my "YES" forecast at 87%. With 5 1/2 months left "stuff" could still happen, so I won't follow @SE_Meyer with 100%. I'm not that BOLD.

Apple is currently the largest company by market cap by a fair margin over Microsoft and Saudi Aramco (https://companiesmarketcap.com/) and is expected to sell more phones this year through upgrades, particularly with 5G networks becoming more available (https://www.forbes.com/sites/tmobile/2021/09/29/why-upgrading-to-5g-phones-and-devices-makes-sense-for-small-business/?sh=3a8de6ec2174). Supply chain issues or maybe greater than expected growth from leading companies are still potential threats . https://www.statista.com/statistics/276306/global-apple-iphone-sales-since-fiscal-year-2007/

The movements in valuation have been steep enough that it seems fully possible one of the three $2T+ companies overtakes Apple's $2.8T by the end of the year if either; Apple report a bad quarter or ends up in a major lawsuit that hurts its multiple or one of the other companies gains some significant momentum. Tesla, at $1T seems a longshot to overtake it, but it isn't impossible with a big enough new story and enough hype. Assigning a 10% chance to a non-US company taking the top spot in the world, either Aramco, TSMC, Tencent or another large tech/energy firm.
Apple has a big gap to Microsoft and Aramco is a long shot to pass them.

I started with @bennybigs' reasoning. If a company is going to overtake Apple, it will most likely be Microsoft. Microsoft's market capitalization is currently 83% of Apple's. Apple is in first place, Microsoft is in second, Saudi Aramco is in third.

Tech stocks move, broadly, similar so the probability of another tech stock having a larger market cap is low. Aramco needs to increase ist market cap by about 40% while growing something like 3-4% last year. Thus it seems highly unlikely that Aramco can manage to surpass Apple from "organic" growth. So the only possibility is a significant reduction of the value of tech stocks combined with gains in the oil industry.
With Microsoft's recent acquisition strategy and areas of relative market dominance there is scope for relative growth ahead of Apple but this seems less likely on balance.
Base this more on the volatility and potential of the energy sector to spike vs Apple's ability to maintain their top seat.
Apple's 2021 Q4 result and the potential to turn iPhone into POS provides some unique valuation runway in 2022 (potential acquisitions may further accelerate the growth).
Apple is due for upgrades on many of their products and 2022 is going to see those upgrades. Besides Samsung did not project any new phone yet for this year.

Microsoft, Google, Amazon, and Saudi Armaco are the main competitors (market caps over $1 trillion). Earning at time of this analysis have AAPL at $105B and MSFT at $73B (includes Activision Blizzard). MSFT trading at 31.9x earnings, AAPL at 26.43. Assuming AAPL trades at same multiple, MSFT would need to trade at 38.4x, GOOG at 39x, and AMZN at 104x. Main threat might be from GOOG with its higher growth rates Saudi Amaco with $174B in earnings (trading at 11x earnings) - would need 16x to match AAPL.
